<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">China (Yunnan).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">The specific name, derived from Latin word meaning the broadest, refers to the forewing with an extremely broad band at apex.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. latissimus" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="species" species="latissimus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">B. latissimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. is similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. herbaceus" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="species" species="herbaceus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">B. herbaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Tsaur &amp; Hsu, 1991, but differs in: (1) left side of periandrium with two spinose processes (in 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. herbaceus" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="species" species="herbaceus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">B. herbaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, left side of periandrium with one spinose process); (2) spinose process on right of periandrium curved downwards (in 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. herbaceus" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="species" species="herbaceus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">B. herbaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, spinose process in the same position curved upwards); (3) anal segment asymmetrical (the latter symmetrical); (4) forewing with one blackish brown spot and two bands (the latter without any marking).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
